\f7\b\fs28 \cf9 \strokec9 The Mouse
\f6\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\qj\partightenfactor0

\fs48 \cf7 \strokec7 Noctivagous shows in the vector-drawing demo that the mouse should\'a0be \
reconfigured to conform to the same\'a0principles as the portable musical instrument.\'a0 \
To recap, as the mouse is used today\'a0it places too much cognitive load on the \
computer user by combining into a\'a0single device, at a single location:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 \
1) steering (moving the cursor) -  the role of the hand on the guitar fretboard.\
2) triggering of functionality (clicking things) - the role of the hand that picks the strings.\
\
The mouse assigns all of that to one hand.\'a0 The reason that happened is the mouse\'a0\
has always attempted to act as a direct extension of the hand.
\f7\b \cf9 \strokec9 \'a0 
\f6\b0 \cf9 \strokec9 But in actuality,\
when there is machine interaction\'a0this merits a separation of roles, just like\
a portable musical instrument.\'a0 There is precedent for separating them in computer\'a0history\
but it was forgotten after the 1970s.\'a0\'a0The 1963 Sketchpad demo by\'a0Ivan Sutherland\'a0\
({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5RyU50qbvzQ"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5RyU50qbvzQ}}) separated the pen from\
the buttons that established\'a0points for the line.\'a0\'a0Making these roles distinct, \
separating them\'a0into\'a0two input locations that make use of use both hands provides \
the user\'a0greater control over software which is likely why Sutherland did not place\
buttons on the pen itself (which is what our mouse is currently).\'a0 \
One obstacle to acceptance in recent times is that there is a notion \
that the more overtly mechancial-feeling a consumer product is,\
like Sutherland\'92s Sketchpad, the less favorably it will be received by the public. \
But when the benefits far outweigh this superficial appearance aspect people\
will eventually recognize the importance.  \
\
With its vector-drawing demo ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://noctivagous.github.io/vector-drawing"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 noctivagous.github.io/vector-drawing}}), \
Noctivagous demonstrates that the trackpad should be left to steer the \
cursor while the\'a0"clicks" occur at a different location, the\'a0keyboard keys.\'a0\'a0\
\cf11 \outl0\strokewidth0 All software conventions\'a0tied to the mouse, such as dragging, \
can be adapted to fit this key-click\'a0+ mouse-steering setup\'a0and the results are \
superior to what is on desktop software today.   In the demo, even dragging objects\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf11 changes into something smoother and light because of what is called a drag-lock, \
that the objects just stick to the cursor.  But the sticking of objects to the cursor \
only works so well when placed inside the bimodal/dual-input setup of keyboard keys + mouse.\'a0 \
For the software developer, a new set of opportunities stemming from the bimodal UI theory \
opens up software.  Established software technologies like node-based programming\
become easier to deal with.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\qj\partightenfactor0
