In the same way that the mouse is made to work in tandem with a separate location for click-buttons, \
Noctivagous explains in a different essay how to apply bimodal/dual-input to multi-touch tablets. \
First, a vertical list of LED-screen-backed buttons has been provided to the sides of the\
touchscreen.  They are backed by LED \cf11 \outl0\strokewidth0 displays (just like on Loupedeck or Streamdeck)\cf9 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec9  \
so that they can swap out functionality.  In this circumstance, they will immeidately expand the range of \
multi-touch devices because they serve to define the touch\'92s functionality before it occurs, \
following the dual-input principle.\'a0 \'a0For example, a button can be provided to the user as \
\'93fill shapes\'94.  Pressing this button sets up every touch to apply this function.  \
Here is one example procedure:\
\
\'97 1. an LED-\cf11 \outl0\strokewidth0 screen\cf9 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec9 -backed button is pressed by the user for \'93\cf11 \outl0\strokewidth0 fill shapes\cf9 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec9 \'94. \cf11 \outl0\strokewidth0 The touch is now defined as \'93fill shapes\'94.\cf9 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec9 \
